We will again work with data from the nycflights13 package.

library(nycflights13)
library(tidyverse)

Exercise 1

Examine the documentation for the datasets airports, flights, and planes. What are the dimensions of each? How are these datasets related?

flights contains all the on-time/delay data for all flights that departed NYC in 2013. airports contains additional metadata about the airports, such as latitude, longitude, time zone, etc. The faa code in airports matches the dest and origin codes in flights . planes contains additional metadata for all the plane tailnumbers in the FAA registry. These can be linked to tailnum in flights.

dim(flights)
[1] 336776     19
dim(airports)
[1] 1458    8
dim(planes)
[1] 3322    9

Suppose you wanted to make a map of the route of every flight. What variables would you need from which datasets? You need the geographic location of the airports (from airports) and the path of flights (i.e., which airports were involved) from flights.

We want to join flights to airports. Note these two datasets have no variables in common so we will have to specify the variable to join by using by =. Check out the documentation for more information.

flights %>% 
  left_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa"))

Exercise 2

Create a new dataset dest_delays with the median arrival delay for each destination. Note this question does not require you to use joins.

dest_delays <- flights %>% 
  group_by(dest) %>% 
  summarize(median_delay = median(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

Exercise 3

Create a new dataset by joining dest_delays and airports. Only include observations that have both delay and airport information. Note dest_delays and flights have no variables in common so you will need to specify the variables to join using by as in the example above.

airport_with_delays <- dest_delays %>% 
  inner_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa"))

Exercise 4

Are all of the rows in dest_delays included in the new dataset you created by joining dest_delays and airports? Use an anti_join to help investigate this issue. Recall anti_join(x,y) returns all rows from x without a match in y.

anti_join(dest_delays, airport_with_delays)

Exercise 5

Is there a relationship between the age of a plane and its delays? The plane tail number is given in the tailnum variable in the flights dataset. The year the plane was manufactured is given in the year variable in the planes dataset.

Start by finding the average arrival delay for each plane and store the resulting dataset in plane_delays.

plane_delays <- flights %>% 
  group_by(tailnum) %>% 
  summarize(avg_arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

Join plane_delays to the planes data using an appropriate join and then use mutate to create an age variable. Note this data is from 2013.

planes <- nycflights13::planes %>% 
  left_join(plane_delays) %>% 
  mutate(age = 2013 - year)

Finally, create an effective visualization of the data to investigate if there a relationship between the age of a plane and its delays. Comment on your conclusions.

ggplot(planes, aes(x = age, y = avg_arr_delay)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  theme_minimal()

BONUS / Extra mapping fun

Try re-creating the visualization below and/or exploring other ways to visualized the flights data spatially.

Some starter code is provided below for creating a basic US map.

library(maps)
library(mapdata)

state <- map_data("state")

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = state, 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = 'lightblue', color = "white") +
  theme_void() +
  coord_fixed(1.3)

Adding on the flight trajectories will require some creative data wrangling. Hint: you will need a dataframe with at least 7 columns: the ID, latitude, and longitude for both the origin and destination airports, and a count column of the number of flights between those dest-origin airports. You can use a geom_curve() layer to create the flight curves; the above plot has curvature = 0.2.

#create data frame of airports, with dest_delay info
#but keep only the "lower 48" states 
#that is, exclude Hawaii and Alaska for plotting purposes
#this can be accomplished by removing timezones
airports_US48 <- airports %>% 
  inner_join(dest_delays, by = c("faa" ="dest")) %>% 
  filter(!(tz %in% c(8, -9, -10)))

#count the number of flights that go to each destination
dest_freq <- flights %>% 
  count(dest)

#add that variable to airports_US48
airports_US48 <- airports_US48 %>% 
  left_join(dest_freq, by = c("faa" = "dest"))

#create data frame with longitude/latitude info
#for the three origin airports
orig_locations <- airports %>% 
  filter(faa %in% c("EWR", "JFK", "LGA")) %>% 
  select(faa, lat, lon)

#add longitude/latitude info of airports for each flight
#use suffix in join function to indicate whether long/lat
#column is for the origin or destination airport
# flights <- flights %>% 
#   left_join(airports, by = c("dest" = "faa")) %>% 
#   left_join(orig_locations, by = c("origin" = "faa"),
#             suffix = c(".dest", ".orig"))

#count the number of times each flight path occurs
#join longitude/latitude info of airports
#use suffix in join function to indicate whether long/lat
#column is for the origin or destination airport
path_count <- flights %>% 
  count(dest, origin) %>% 
  inner_join(airports_US48 %>% select(-n), 
             by = c("dest" = "faa")) %>% 
  inner_join(orig_locations, by = c("origin" = "faa"),
            suffix = c(".dest", ".orig"))
  

ggplot() + 
  #creates base layer of lightblue state map
  geom_polygon(data = state, 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
               fill = 'lightblue', color = "white") + 
  #add points for each airport location, size mapped to 
  #number of flights that travel to that destination
  geom_point(data = airports_US48, aes(x = lon, y = lat, 
                                       size = n), alpha = 0.8) +
  #add flight paths, transparency mapped to number of flights
  #that followed that origin-dest path
  geom_curve(data = path_count, aes(x = lon.dest, 
                                    y = lat.dest, 
                                    xend = lon.orig, 
                                    yend = lat.orig,
                                    alpha = n), 
             curvature = .2) +
  theme_void() +
  coord_fixed(1.3) +
  guides(alpha = "none") +
  labs(title = "Flights from NYC to continguous 48 states",
       subtitle = "from nycflights 2013 data",
       size = "Number of flights to destination") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
